# üöÄ feature request

### Relevant Package
This feature request should be relevant for the angular compiler.

### Description
We have an angular application that is used by multiple customers. For each customer, we have a different set of styles that need to be applied for branding the application.

The branding mainly lives in SCSS variables. We have a base SCSS file where we define default values for all variables (styles, shadows, borders, ...). Then, we have a SCSS file for each customer where we override the default values.

Consider the following project structure:
```
- angular.json
- package.json
- ...
- src
  - variables.scss
  - branding
    - _branding.scss
    - customer_a
        - _branding.scss
    - customer_b
        - _branding.scss
```

`src/branding/_branding.scss` defines default values for variables:

```scss
$color-primary: #ff7f50;
$color-secondary: #7fffd4;
$logo-url: url("/assets/logo.png");
```

The customer-specific stylesheet, for example `src/branding/customer_a/_branding.scss`, imports the default variables and overrides them:

```scss
@import "../_branding.scss";
$color-primary: #7b68ee;
$logo-url: url("/assets/customer_a.png");
```

The customer-specific styles get included by setting the `stylePreprocessorOptions.includePaths`-property in `angular.json` for each customer:

```json

{
  ...
  "build": {
    "configurations": {
      "customer_a": {
        "stylePreprocessorOptions": {
          "includePaths": [
            "src/branding/customer_a"
          ]
        }
      },
      "customer_b": {
        "stylePreprocessorOptions": {
          "includePaths": [
            "src/branding/customer_b"
          ]
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

```

This allows us to import and use the styles in the component-specific scss files, e.g. `app.component.scss`, like this:

```scss

@import "_branding" // <- This statements imports whichever file has been included using stylePreprocessorOptions.includePaths

.logo {
  background-image: $logo-url;
}

```

While is approach technically works, it requires us to build the whole application once for each customer.

Currently we are building our (quite complex) application over 10 times for each release, and every time all the application logic, components, dependencies (which are the same for every customer) are needlessly getting compiled and bundled over and over again. This takes a very long time, especially on our CD pipeline.

I think there could be a better approach to this. All we __really__ need to build multiple times are the styles. I think a way that allows us to bundle styles only - perhaps by setting a flag in the angular cli - would be a great addition and allow for more sophisticated branding and white-labelling capabilities.


### Describe the solution you'd like
I think having an optional flag (such as `--onlyStyles`) for the `ng build` command would be a great experience.

This way we could build the whole application once and then build only styles for each customer configuration. Of course this would be feasible only if building all styles - including those referenced by angular components - would significantly improve build duration.

### Describe alternatives you've considered

We have considered and tested the following alternatives:

#### CSS custom properties (variables) + lazy loading

One alternative we considered is using CSS variables instead of Sass variables. This way we could have a stylesheet per customer defining CSS variables which override the defaults. We could then easily include each stylesheet as a lazy loaded stylesheet and have them built and emitted in a __single__ build.

All we then need to do is add some initialization logic that lazily loads the correct stylesheet.

The problem we have with this approach is that we heavily rely on Sass functions to modify colors and the like (think `mix()`, `lighten()` etc.). For obvious reasons, CSS custom properties cannot be passed into Sass functions as arguments.

While this approach might work perfectly for applications that are not dependent on Sass functions, it is infeasible for those who want to heavily leverage Sass' capabilities.

#### Build styles independently from angular's toolchain

For this approach, we would build the scss styles using any external tools, e.g. webpack or gulp. We could setup a task that, for each customer, fetches all Sass-files in the project folder, prepends the customer-specific styles and builds the resulting CSS. This way, the angular project would only need to be bundled once.

However, this approach has some drawbacks: We cannot make use of great features like view encapsulation. It also introduces additional build-tools, polluting the otherwise very tidy angular-cli workflow. 

____

I hope I was able to describe the problem and possible solution sufficiently. If there is any additional information I can provide please let me know.

#### Documentation Feedback

Couldn't find any information in regard to how to use `DrawingMananger` with Maps component.
I have tried following snippet but it neither works or throws any error:
